    581                  //cycle could very easily cause the debugger to error and we don't
    582                  //want that.  While the power management state machine will stall
    583                  //if CSYSPWRUPREQ is set (to avoid the situation just described),
    584                  //in this stalled state the chip will not be responsive to wake
    585                  //events.  To be sensitive to wake events, we must handle them in
    586                  //software instead.  To accomplish this, we request that the
    587                  //CSYSPWRUPACK be inhibited (which will indicate the debugger is not
    588                  //connected).  But, we cannot induce deep sleep until CSYSPWRUPREQ/ACK
    589                  //go low and these are under the debuggers control, so we must stall
    590                  //and wait here.  If there is a wake event during this time, break
    591                  //out and wake like normal.  If the ACK eventually clears,
    592                  //we can proceed into deep sleep.  The CMHV->CSYSPWRUPACKINHIBIT
    593                  //functionality will hold off the debugger (by holding off the ACK)
    594                  //until we are safely past and out of deep sleep.  The power management
    595                  //state machine then becomes responsible for clearing
